1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,610
There's a story often told about the job attitudes of three bricklayers.

2
00:00:04,640 --> 00:00:07,649
It's a classic, so let's go over it again.

3
00:00:08,080 --> 00:00:10,130
When asked, what are you doing?

4
00:00:10,160 --> 00:00:13,330
The first bricklayer replied, laying brick.

5
00:00:13,520 --> 00:00:17,570
The second answered, making $9.30 an hour.

6
00:00:17,680 --> 00:00:19,490
And the third said, me?

7
00:00:19,600 --> 00:00:22,769
Why, I'm building the world's greatest cathedral.

8
00:00:23,520 --> 00:00:28,450
Now, the story doesn't tell us what happened to these bricklayers in later years,

9
00:00:28,480 --> 00:00:30,210
but what do you think happened?

10
00:00:30,560 --> 00:00:35,730
Chances are that the first two bricklayers remained just that, bricklayers.

11
00:00:35,840 --> 00:00:37,250
They lacked vision.

12
00:00:37,280 --> 00:00:39,010
They lacked job respect.

13
00:00:39,120 --> 00:00:43,409
There was nothing behind them to propel them forward to greater success.

14
00:00:43,680 --> 00:00:52,370
But you can wager every cent you have, the bricklayer who visualized himself as building a great cathedral did not remain a bricklayer.

15
00:00:52,480 --> 00:00:57,890
Perhaps he became a foreman, or perhaps a contractor, or possibly an architect.

16
00:00:58,080 --> 00:01:00,210
He moved forward and upward.

17
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:00,850
Why?

18
00:01:01,040 --> 00:01:03,809
Because thinking does make it so.

19
00:01:04,160 --> 00:01:05,409
Bricklayer No.

20
00:01:05,409 --> 00:01:11,250
3 was tuned to thought channels that pointed the way to self-development in his work.

21
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:17,730
Job thinking tells a lot about a person and his potential for larger responsibility.

22
00:01:18,240 --> 00:01:23,169
A friend who operates a personnel selection firm said this to me recently.

23
00:01:23,600 --> 00:01:31,330
One thing we always look for in appraising a job applicant for a client is how the applicant thinks about his present job.

24
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:37,890
We are always favorably impressed when we find that an applicant thinks his present job is important,

25
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:41,250
even though there may be something about it he doesn't like.

26
00:01:41,600 --> 00:01:42,210
Why?

27
00:01:42,400 --> 00:01:43,409
Simply this.

28
00:01:43,600 --> 00:01:50,450
If the applicant feels his present job is important, odds are that he will take pride in his next job,

29
00:01:50,480 --> 00:01:51,010
too.

30
00:01:51,520 --> 00:01:58,529
We've found an amazingly close correlation between a person's job respect and his job performance.

31
00:01:59,280 --> 00:02:07,330
Like your appearance, the way you think toward your work says things about you to your superiors, associates, and subordinates.

32
00:02:07,520 --> 00:02:10,690
In fact, to everyone with whom you come in contact.

33
00:02:11,200 --> 00:02:18,289
A few months ago I spent several hours with a friend who is personnel director for an appliance manufacturer.

34
00:02:18,720 --> 00:02:21,090
We talked about building men.

35
00:02:21,200 --> 00:02:25,810
He explained his personnel audit system and what he had learned from it.

36
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:30,450
We have about 800 non-production people, he began.

37
00:02:30,800 --> 00:02:37,570
Under our personnel audit system, an assistant and I interview each employee every six months.

38
00:02:37,760 --> 00:02:39,330
Our purpose is simple.

39
00:02:39,520 --> 00:02:42,769
We want to learn how we can help him in his job.

40
00:02:43,120 --> 00:02:47,890
We think this is a good practice because each person working with us is important,

41
00:02:47,920 --> 00:02:50,130
else he wouldn't be on the payroll.

42
00:02:50,640 --> 00:02:55,490
We are careful not to ask the employees any point-blank questions.

43
00:02:55,760 --> 00:02:59,570
Instead, we encourage him to talk about whatever he wants to.

44
00:02:59,840 --> 00:03:02,370
We aim to get his honest impressions.

45
00:03:02,480 --> 00:03:10,210
After each interview, we fill out a rating form on the employee's attitudes toward specific aspects of his job.

46
00:03:10,720 --> 00:03:13,409
Now here's something I've learned, he went on.

47
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:19,010
Our employees fit into one of two categories, Group A and Group B,

48
00:03:19,120 --> 00:03:22,210
on the basis of how they think toward their jobs.

49
00:03:22,640 --> 00:03:29,330
The persons in Group B talk mainly about security, company retirement plans, sick leave policy,

50
00:03:29,440 --> 00:03:38,529
extra time off, what we're doing to improve the insurance program, and if they will be asked to work overtime next March as they were last March.

51
00:03:38,880 --> 00:03:45,090
They also talk a lot about disagreeable features of their job, things they don't like in fellow workers,

52
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:46,049
and so on.

53
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:52,529
People in Group B, and they include close to eighty percent of all non-production personnel,

54
00:03:52,720 --> 00:03:56,049
view their jobs as a sort of necessary evil.

55
00:03:56,640 --> 00:04:00,450
The Group A fellow sees his job through different glasses.

56
00:04:00,640 --> 00:04:07,330
He is concerned about his future and wants concrete suggestions on what he can do to make faster progress.

57
00:04:07,520 --> 00:04:11,169
He doesn't expect us to give him anything except a chance.

58
00:04:11,440 --> 00:04:14,529
The Group A people think on a broader scale.

59
00:04:14,720 --> 00:04:17,490
They make suggestions for improving the business.

60
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:21,169
They regard these interviews in my office as constructive.

61
00:04:21,440 --> 00:04:27,490
But the Group B people often feel our personnel audit system is just a brainwashing affair,

62
00:04:27,490 --> 00:04:29,490
and they're glad to get it over with.